    {
      "question": "What is the definition of 'recyclable in practice and at scale'?",
      "answer": "Recyclable 'in practice and at scale' means successful post-consumer collection, sorting, and recycling, which is proven to work in practice and at scale. The test and threshold for assessment is a 30% recycling rate in multiple regions, collectively representing at least 400 million people. A possible alternative, especially relevant for more local players, is to check if a 30% post-consumer recycling rate is achieved in all the markets where a packaging is sold."
    },
    {
      "question": "What is the definition of 'technically recyclable'?",
      "answer": "Technically recyclable considers the technical potential to recycle a packaging, but does not take into account if the collection, sorting, and recycling of the packaging happens in practice, at scale, and with reasonable economics. Technically recyclable plastics must be made of plastic that is collected for recycling, has a market value, and/or is supported by a legislatively mandated program."
